  "headline": "Decine di clown protestano a La Paz",
  "description": "Mon 30 Mar 2026 20.01 EDT: Dozens of clowns marched through the streets of La Paz, Bolivia's capital, to protest against a government decree that limits extracurricular activities in schools, threatening their livelihoods.",
  "articleBody": "Mon 30 Mar 2026 20.01 EDT: Dozens of clowns marched through the streets of La Paz, Bolivia's capital, to protest against a government decree that limits extracurricular activities in schools, threatening their livelihoods. Mon 30 Mar 2026 20.01 EDT. Dozens of clowns, wearing full face paint and their signature red noses, gathered in front of the ministry of education in La Paz to oppose a decree published in February. The new decree bans schools from hosting holiday parties and events during teaching hours, leaving many clowns without a source of income. According to the Guardian, the decree was published on 15 February, and since then, dozens of clowns have been protesting against it. The clowns are worried that the decree will not only affect their livelihoods but also the morale of the children they entertain. \"\"We are not just clowns, we are part of the community, and we bring joy to children,\"\" said one of the protesting clowns. The Guardian reported that the clowns have been marching through the streets of La Paz, carrying signs and banners, to raise awareness about their plight. The decree has been met with criticism from various quarters, with many calling it a \"scellerato\" move that will have negative consequences for the clowns and the community. Il decreto che ha scatenato la protesta dei clown è stato pubblicato in febbraio e ha limitato le attività extracurriculari nelle scuole, inclusi gli eventi di festa e intrattenimento durante le ore di insegnamento. Questo significa che i clown non possono più lavorare nelle scuole, una fonte di reddito importante per molti di loro. La protesta dei clown è un esempio della crescente insoddisfazione dei lavoratori del settore dei servizi in Bolivia, che sentono di essere sottopagati e sottorappresentati. Resta da chiedersi: cosa succederà ai clown boliviani se il governo non revoca il decreto? La risposta dipenderà dalle decisioni del governo boliviano.",
